list.markScheme:
- A rational function is undefined when the denominator is equal to zero.

  $$
  \begin{align*}
  2x+k&=0\\[6pt]
  x&=-\frac{k}{2}
  \end{align*}
  $$

  Any other value for $x$ is valid.
  Hence we get the domain

  $$
  \begin{align*}
  &\hspace{-0.5em}\tcbhighmath{x \in \mathbb{R}, x\neq-\frac{k}{2}}\tag*{\textbf{\textcolor{black}{A1}}}
  \end{align*}
  $$

- We are trying to find the function $y=f^{-1}(x)$.
  The definition of an inverse states that

  $$
  \begin{align*}
      (f \circ f^{-1})(x)&=x
  \end{align*}
  $$

  Hence we can rewrite this to get

  $$
  \begin{align*}
      f(f^{-1}(x))&=x\\[6pt]
      f(y)&=x
  \end{align*}
  $$

  Hence we get

  $$
  \begin{align*}
  f(y)&=x\\[6pt]
  \frac{3y+4}{2y+k}&=x
  \end{align*}
  $$

  Recall, we want $y=f^{-1}(x)$ therefore we should rearrange this to make $y$ the subject.

  $$
  \begin{align*}
  x(2y+k)&=3y+4\\[6pt]
  2xy+kx&=3y+4
  \end{align*}
  $$

  To isolate $y$, we move all of the $y$ terms to one side and then factorise out $y$.

  $$
  \begin{align*}
  2xy-3y&=-kx+4\\[6pt]
  y(2x-3)&=-kx+4\tag*{\textbf{\textcolor{black}{(M1)}}}\\[6pt]
  y&=\frac{-kx+4}{2x-3}\\[10pt]
  &\hspace{-3.2em}\answer{f^{-1}(x)=\dfrac{-kx+4}{2x-3}}\tag*{\textbf{\textcolor{black}{A1}}}
  \end{align*}
  $$

- A self-inverse function is such that $f(x)\equiv f^{-1}(x)$.
  Therefore

  $$
  \begin{align*}
  \frac{3x+4}{2x+k}&\equiv \frac{-kx+4}{2x-3}
  \end{align*}
  $$

  Comparing either the numerators or denominators,

  $$
  \begin{align*}
  3x+4&=-kx+4
  \end{align*}
  $$

  Therefore

  $$
  \begin{align*}
  &\hspace{-0.5em}\tcbhighmath{k=-3}\tag*{\textbf{\textcolor{black}{A1}}}
  \end{align*}
  $$

- The vertical asymptote occurs when the denominator of the fraction is equal to zero.

  $$
  \begin{align*}
      2+a&=0\\[6pt]
      &\hspace{-0.525em}\tcbhighmath{a=-2} \tag*{\textbf{A1}}
  \end{align*}
  $$

- From the information given we know that the point $(\tfrac{2}{3},0)$ lies on the curve.
  Hence, we can create an equation and solve it for $b$.

  $$
  \begin{align*}
      0&=b+\frac{4}{\tfrac{2}{3}-2} \tag*{\textbf{M1A1}}\\[6pt]
      b&=-\frac{4}{-\tfrac{4}{3}}\\[6pt]
      &\hspace{-0.525em}\tcbhighmath{b=3} \tag*{\textbf{A1}}
  \end{align*}
  $$

- The horizontal asymptote occurs as $x \rightarrow \pm \infty$. We can see that as this happens the fractional part of $f(x)$ will tend to $0$.
  Hence the equation of the horizontal asymptote is

  $$
  \begin{align*}
      y&=3+\frac{4}{\pm \infty-2}\\[6pt]
      &\hspace{-0.525em}\tcbhighmath{y=3} \tag*{\textbf{A1}}
  \end{align*}
  $$

  The answer must be given as an equation, either $y=3$ or $f(x)=3$.
